  "transcript": [
    {
      "id": "line-000",
      "start": 0.0,
      "end": 9.98,
      "text": "This is a Libervox recording. All Libervox recordings are in the public domain. For more information or to volunteer, please visit Libervox.org.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-001",
      "start": 10.96,
      "end": 19.14,
      "text": "ASOP's fables, the shipwrecked man and the sea. A shipwrecked man cast up on the beach, fell asleep after his struggle with the waves.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-002",
      "start": 19.76,
      "end": 32.86,
      "text": "When he woke up, he bitterly reproached the sea for its treachery and enticing men with its smooth and smiling surface, and then when they were well embarked, turning inferior upon them, and sending both ship and sailors to destruction.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-003",
      "start": 34.0,
      "end": 44.24,
      "text": "The sea arose in the form of a woman, and replied, lay not the blame upon me, O sailor, but on the winds. By nature, I am as calm and safe as the land itself.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-004",
      "start": 44.88,
      "end": 54.32,
      "text": "But the winds fall upon me with their gusts and gales and lash me into a fury that is not natural to me. End of the shipwrecked man and the sea.",
      "note": ""
    }
  ],
